{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-997739243224f54d", "type": "tool_result", "content": "# Common Voice: A Massively-Multilingual Speech Corpus\narXiv: 1912.06670\nAuthors: Rosana Ardila, Megan Branson, Kelly Davis, Michael Henretty, Michael Kohler, Josh Meyer, Reuben Morais, Lindsay Saunders, Francis M. Tyers, Gregor Weber\nYear: 2019 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_dataset\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Presentation of Common Voice, a massively-multilingual, crowd-sourced speech corpus released under a public domain license.\n  2. Implementation of a scalable data collection and validation pipeline that organically supports new languages through community effort.\n  3. Demonstration of multilingual automatic speech recognition via transfer learning, yielding an average Character Error Rate improvement across twelve target languages.\n  4. Publication of the first ever end-to-end automatic speech recognition results for the majority of the twelve investigated target languages.\n\nTags: ASR", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "aa5dd46b-1c58-4cf7-afee-45e66cfdb778", "uuid": "0dbd65ef-3371-45c3-8362-f99786f46405", "timestamp": "2026-07-14T16:51:23.610Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "# Common Voice: A Massively-Multilingual Speech Corpus\narXiv: 1912.06670\nAuthors: Rosana Ardila, Megan Branson, Kelly Davis, Michael Henretty, Michael Kohler, Josh Meyer, Reuben Morais, Lindsay Saunders, Francis M. Tyers, Gregor Weber\nYear: 2019 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_dataset\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Presentation of Common Voice, a massively-multilingual, crowd-sourced speech corpus released under a public domain license.\n  2. Implementation of a scalable data collection and validation pipeline that organically supports new languages through community effort.\n  3. Demonstration of multilingual automatic speech recognition via transfer learning, yielding an average Character Error Rate improvement across twelve target languages.\n  4. Publication of the first ever end-to-end automatic speech recognition results for the majority of the twelve investigated target languages.\n\nTags: ASR", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-b7497f1e8e78ca2a", "type": "tool_result", "content": "# GigaSpeech 2: An Evolving, Large-Scale and Multi-domain ASR Corpus for Low-Resource Languages with Automated Crawling, Transcription and Refinement\narXiv: 2406.11546\nAuthors: Yifan Yang, Zheshu Song, Jianheng Zhuo, Mingyu Cui, Jinpeng Li, Bo Yang, Yexing Du, Ziyang Ma, Xunying Liu, Ziyuan Wang, Ke Li, Shuai Fan, Kai Yu, Wei-Qiang Zhang, Guoguo Chen, Xie Chen\nYear: 2024 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_dataset\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We release GigaSpeech 2, a large-scale, multi-domain, multilingual ASR corpus containing raw and refined versions of automatically transcribed Thai, Indonesian, and Vietnamese speech.\n  2. We develop an automated pipeline for data crawling, transcription, and label refinement that constructs large-scale speech datasets without relying on labeled data.\n  3. We propose a modified Noisy Student Training method that iteratively refines flawed pseudo labels through scaling, relabeling, and filtering to significantly improve data quality.\n  4. We release challenging and realistic speech recognition test sets for Thai, Indonesian, and Vietnamese that better reflect real-world ASR scenarios than previous public test sets.\n  5. We demonstrate that ASR models trained on GigaSpeech 2 outperform competitive baselines, including Whisper large-v3 and commercial services, across multiple evaluation sets.\n\nTags: ASR", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "aa5dd46b-1c58-4cf7-afee-45e66cfdb778", "uuid": "12aa52c2-cd13-4def-a68b-3c57dc7ebd5e", "timestamp": "2026-07-14T16:51:23.833Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "# GigaSpeech 2: An Evolving, Large-Scale and Multi-domain ASR Corpus for Low-Resource Languages with Automated Crawling, Transcription and Refinement\narXiv: 2406.11546\nAuthors: Yifan Yang, Zheshu Song, Jianheng Zhuo, Mingyu Cui, Jinpeng Li, Bo Yang, Yexing Du, Ziyang Ma, Xunying Liu, Ziyuan Wang, Ke Li, Shuai Fan, Kai Yu, Wei-Qiang Zhang, Guoguo Chen, Xie Chen\nYear: 2024 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_dataset\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We release GigaSpeech 2, a large-scale, multi-domain, multilingual ASR corpus containing raw and refined versions of automatically transcribed Thai, Indonesian, and Vietnamese speech.\n  2. We develop an automated pipeline for data crawling, transcription, and label refinement that constructs large-scale speech datasets without relying on labeled data.\n  3. We propose a modified Noisy Student Training method that iteratively refines flawed pseudo labels through scaling, relabeling, and filtering to significantly improve data quality.\n  4. We release challenging and realistic speech recognition test sets for Thai, Indonesian, and Vietnamese that better reflect real-world ASR scenarios than previous public test sets.\n  5. We demonstrate that ASR models trained on GigaSpeech 2 outperform competitive baselines, including Whisper large-v3 and commercial services, across multiple evaluation sets.\n\nTags: ASR", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a7ead176d010e141", "type": "tool_result", "content": "# Robust Speech Recognition via Large-Scale Weak Supervision\narXiv: 2212.04356\nAuthors: Alec Radford, Jong Wook Kim, Tao Xu, Greg Brockman, Christine McLeavey, Ilya Sutskever\nYear: 2022 | Venue: \nTopic: asr\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Scaling weakly supervised speech recognition to 680,000 hours of multilingual and multitask data enables robust zero-shot transfer without fine-tuning.\n  2. Demonstrating that zero-shot Whisper models approach human-level accuracy and robustness on English speech recognition benchmarks.\n  3. Introducing a single multitask format using special tokens to jointly train a unified model for speech recognition, translation, language identification, and voice activity detection.\n  4. Developing effective decoding heuristics, such as temperature fallback and timestamp constraints, to reliably transcribe long-form audio.\n  5. Releasing the Whisper models and inference code to serve as a foundation for future research on robust speech processing.\n\nTags: ASR, ASR/训练-弱监督", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "aa5dd46b-1c58-4cf7-afee-45e66cfdb778", "uuid": "b61d8f48-8ea6-416c-b626-1593d0353d87", "timestamp": "2026-07-14T16:51:24.062Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "# Robust Speech Recognition via Large-Scale Weak Supervision\narXiv: 2212.04356\nAuthors: Alec Radford, Jong Wook Kim, Tao Xu, Greg Brockman, Christine McLeavey, Ilya Sutskever\nYear: 2022 | Venue: \nTopic: asr\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Scaling weakly supervised speech recognition to 680,000 hours of multilingual and multitask data enables robust zero-shot transfer without fine-tuning.\n  2. Demonstrating that zero-shot Whisper models approach human-level accuracy and robustness on English speech recognition benchmarks.\n  3. Introducing a single multitask format using special tokens to jointly train a unified model for speech recognition, translation, language identification, and voice activity detection.\n  4. Developing effective decoding heuristics, such as temperature fallback and timestamp constraints, to reliably transcribe long-form audio.\n  5. Releasing the Whisper models and inference code to serve as a foundation for future research on robust speech processing.\n\nTags: ASR, ASR/训练-弱监督", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
